      <p>Let <m>A=\{1, 2, 3\}, B=\{2, 4, 6, 8\}, C=\{0, 1\}</m>.</p>
      

      <exercise><statement><p>Let <m>f:A\rightarrow B</m> be given by <m>f(1)=4, f(2)=8, f(3)=2</m>. True or false: <m>f</m> is a function.</p></statement>
      <answer>True</answer></exercise>

      <exercise><statement><p>Let <m>f:A\rightarrow B</m> be given by <m>f(1)=2, f(2)=4, f(3)=2</m>. True or false: <m>f</m> is a function.</p></statement>
      <answer>True</answer></exercise>


      <exercise><statement><p>Let <m>f:B\rightarrow C</m> be given by <m>f(2)=0, f(4)=1</m>. True or false: <m>f</m> is a function.</p></statement>
      <answer><p>False. <m>4, 6</m> don't map anywhere.</p></answer></exercise>

      <exercise><statement><p>Let <m>f:B\rightarrow C</m> be given by <m>f(2)=0, f(4)=1, f(6)=1, f(8)=1</m>. True or false: <m>f</m> is a function.</p></statement>
      <answer>True</answer></exercise>

      <exercise><statement><p>Let <m>f:C\rightarrow C</m> be given by <m>f(0)=0, f(0)=1, f(1)=0, f(1)=1</m>. True or false: <m>f</m> is a function.</p></statement>
      <answer><p>False. 0 maps to two different values.</p></answer></exercise>

      <exercise><statement><p>Let <m>f:A\times C\rightarrow C</m> be given by <m>f(a, c)=c</m>. Find the preimage of <m>0\in C</m>.</p></statement>
      <answer><m>\{(1, 0), (2, 0), (3, 0)\}</m></answer></exercise>



    

